{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PpXRRudHbY6dYcNWsxk23i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n- Prometheus listens on port 9090 internally, the service maps it to port 8000.\n- Prometheus's config only scrapes `localhost:9090` (itself).\n- RabbitMQ pods expose metrics on port 15692.\n- There's a headless service `rabbitmq-headless` which allows addressing individual pods.\n\nThe fix is to update the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a scrape job for RabbitMQ. I'll use the headless service to target each pod individually using static_configs.\n\nFor a StatefulSet with 3 pods (rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2), the DNS names via headless service are:\n- `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless:15692`\n- `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless:15692`\n- `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless:15692`\n\nAfter updating the ConfigMap, I need to reload Prometheus. Since it was started with `--web.enable-lifecycle`, I can send a POST to `/-/reload` to reload the config without restarting. I'll use the curl-test pod to send the reload request to Prometheus's port 9090, or I could just rollout restart the deployment to force a reload.\n\nLet me patch the ConfigMap first, then trigger the reload.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1584,"cache_read_input_tokens":31449,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1584},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"183c96f9-459b-4611-b264-4395e252765f","uuid":"7af9d877-1ac1-4005-b6b5-047fbc48961a","request_id":"req_011CcRLSJwTwnrdXShw2fwwX"}
